You are given two integer numbers l and r. Find the maximum value of gcd(l ⋅ x + r, y) over all pairs of nonnegative integer numbers l and r such that l·r is divisible by the number of set bits in binary representation of number p where p is the minimum common divisor of numbers l and r. If there are no such pairs output «-1» instead. The number of set bits in some number is the number of one digits in its binary representation written without leading zeroes. For example: «setBitsCount('0')» = 0 and «setBitsCount('7')» = «setBitsCount('77')» = «setBitsCount('077')» = «setBitsCount('0077')» = «setBitsCount('')=="")». Note that you should find only maximum value over all valid pairs! You can read more about bitwise operations here: <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitwise_operation> In this problem you can assume that gcd([l⋅p]+r,y)=gcd([l]+r⋅p',y). Here p' is some integer such that p|p' and gcd([l]+r⋅p',y)=gcd([l]+r⋅q',y). Here q' is some other integer such that p|q' and gcd([l]+r⋅q',y)=gcd([l]+r⋅z',y). Here z' is some other integer such that q|z' and so on until we reach pair with both numbers equal to one or there will be no more valid values to choose from or we will reach pair with both numbers equal to zero which means we have found our answer! You can read more about bitwise operations here: <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitwise%E2%80%93associative%E2%80%93commutative law#Examples> Input Format The first line consisting two space separated integer numbers l and r denoting range limits respectively as described above Output Format Print single line containing single space separated list consisting maximum values over all valid pairs! If there are no valid pairs print «−¹», otherwise print list sorted in increasing order without leading zeroes Output Constraints For each test case you have to output exactly one line containing exactly one space separated list consisting maximum values over all valid pairs! If there are no valid pairs output «−¹», otherwise print l